                            <comment id="12908206" author="yseeley@gmail.com" created="Fri, 10 Sep 2010 22:05:14 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Here&apos;s a patch that implements the suggestions &lt;br/&gt;
from &lt;a href=&quot;http://search.lucidimagination.com/search/document/2e625d76f2b1fb78/missing_q_gives_500_error&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://search.lucidimagination.com/search/document/2e625d76f2b1fb78/missing_q_gives_500_error&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12908346" author="yseeley@gmail.com" created="Sat, 11 Sep 2010 17:29:24 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;committed.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12908370" author="lancenorskog" created="Sat, 11 Sep 2010 21:27:34 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;+many&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13240155" author="dsmiley" created="Wed, 28 Mar 2012 04:25:07 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;By the way, this issue is actually a duplicate of &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SOLR-435&quot; title=&quot;QParser must validate existence/absence of &amp;quot;q&amp;quot; parameter&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SOLR-435&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SOLR-435&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; which I recently resolved by backporting this patch to 3x.  I also made improvements (3x &amp;amp; 4x), namely added an empty string check for &apos;q&apos;, dismax support, and a test (by Hoss).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13539376" author="dsmiley" created="Tue, 25 Dec 2012 05:21:52 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I troubleshooted a user&apos;s query just now, discovering that the problem was that he had no &apos;q&apos; parameter, and thus his &apos;fq&apos; was irrelevant. Embarrassingly, I didn&apos;t notice this immediately.  It&apos;s wonderful that a blank q no longer throws an error, as shown in the title of this issue.  But what good is search that has no &apos;q&apos; parameter at all?  It should be an error.  &apos;course if &amp;#42;:&amp;#42; were the default then this would be a non-issue &amp;#8211; my preference but it&apos;s too late to argue that now.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
